- The snake is allowed to move through its own body.

- The snake can wrap around the grid. Moving left outside the grid will bring the snake on the other side of the grid, still inside it.
- The apple can appear anywhere in the grid.
- The snake can go through the apple.
- In case of multiple snakes on the same cell, the snake with the lower id (closer to 0) is removed.
- In case of multiple snakes on the same cell with the same id, nothing happens.
</rules>
<grid>
The grid is a 2D matrix of `grid_size x grid_size` cells. Each cell has one of the following values:
- A number from 0 to `grid_size ^ 2 - 1`. This is the id of the snake on that cell. The snake id's go from 0 to infinity.
- The letter 'A' (upper case). This represents an apple.
- The snake's own id surrounded by dots like this: '1' becomes '.1.'.
- The letter '.' (upper case). This is an empty cell.
<important>
The grid always starts with the apples on cells `apple_x, apple_y` and `apple_x + grid_size - 1, apple_y + grid_size - 1`, if there is space for it (it doesn't wrap around).
</important>
</grid>
<snake>
A snake is a set of cells that form a chain. The first cell (the head) has the following extra rules: 
- It can change direction in any cell (except when it is wrapping around).
- It can wrap around the grid.
- It may not eat more than one apple per frame.
- Its direction can change by 90 degrees instantly (for example from up to right).
</snake>
<direction>
The direction of the snake is one of the following: 'UP', 'DOWN', 'LEFT', 'RIGHT'.
The direction of a snake is the direction of its head.
</direction>
<point>
A point is obtained when a snake eats an apple. The snake's size increases by one after eating an apple.
</point>
<die>
A snake dies when any of its cells overlap with another snake's cell, or with its own cell (when looping around).
</die>
<game_rules>
The following rules apply for each frame:
1) The snakes move one cell forward in their direction.
2) If the head of a snake is on the same cell as an apple, the snake eats it. The snake obtains a point and grows.
3) If two or more snakes have their heads in the same cell, both (or all) snakes die.
4) If any part of a snake loops around the grid, the whole snake dies.
</game_rules>
<win>
The game ends when there is only one snake left. The last snake standing wins.
</win>
